SP.L:
I am fortunate to prevent so great a trouble;
There is a business, sir, wherein I must desire your
favour.

SP.P:
Have a care, Jack; I love pleasure as well as thou;
but to obtain it at the expence of every virtue, is rather
paying too dear for it.

I'll not be a witness of your passages myself;
these will report as much as I desire. Sir, if you be
beaten, I am satisfied.

Young Barnacle, and the vinegar bottle his man;
he has business of much import with you! he wou'd be
your rival with Penelope.

I am a little out of Greek at present, Dwindle;
but for Latin, history, and philosophy—What is he
reading, Dwindle?

My nephew understands Greek, lady; ay, and
Latin too, and geography, and poetry, and philosophy;
and is withal as valiant—

A fair riddance; we have enough o' th' tribe;
I am sorry I cannot furnish her expedition with a pair of
my own garters.
